 What is a Clustered Index?

> A clustered index sorts and stores the rows of a table physically in the order of the index key.



Think of it like:

ğŸ—‚ï¸ A dictionary or phonebook:

Everything is physically arranged in sorted order

You donâ€™t search randomly â€” itâ€™s already ordered by Name (the index)


In SQL terms:

If a table has a clustered index on EmployeeID, the actual data in the table is sorted by EmployeeID



---

ğŸ§  Key Points (in plain English)

Feature Explanation

âœ… Physical order Clustered index rearranges the actual rows in the table
âœ… Only one allowed Each table can have only one clustered index because you canâ€™t sort a table in multiple ways physically
âœ… Automatically created When you create a primary key, SQL Server usually automatically creates a clustered index
âœ… Fast performance Searching, sorting, range queries, and joins are faster on indexed columns
ğŸ“¦ Actual data = index The clustered index is the table. There is no separate structure like in non-clustered index



---

ğŸ§ª Real-life Analogy:

ğŸ“š Imagine a library where books are physically arranged by Book ID:

If you're looking for Book ID 104, the librarian quickly goes to the exact shelf â†’ fast!

You can't have one shelf arranged by Book ID and another by Book Title â€” because the physical layout can only follow one sorting rule


Thatâ€™s why a table can only have one clustered index.


---

ğŸ“Œ Syntax to Create a Clustered Index

CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX IX_Employee_EmpID
ON Employee(EmpID);

Or, when you create a primary key:

CREATE TABLE Employee (
    EmpID INT PRIMARY KEY, -- Clustered index automatically created
    Name VARCHAR(100),
    Salary INT
);


---

âœ… When to Use Clustered Index

On primary key or any frequently searched column

On columns used in sorting or range queries (BETWEEN, <, >)

On columns with unique or nearly unique values



---

âŒ When Not to Use It

On columns with frequent updates (e.g., timestamps)

On columns with lots of duplicates (like Gender)

If the data is inserted randomly and might cause fragmentation



---

ğŸ†š Clustered vs Non-Clustered Index

Feature Clustered Index Non-Clustered Index

Data order Physically sorted Separate structure
Number per table Only one Many allowed
Storage Data is the index Stores only a pointer to actual row
Faster for Sorting, searching ranges Lookup of specific columns
Use case Primary key or natural order columns Frequently filtered but not primary key



---

ğŸ§  Interview Tip:

Q: Can a table have multiple clustered indexes?
A: âŒ No. Only one, because the table can only be sorted one way physically.

Q: What happens if I insert a new row in a clustered index table?
A: SQL Server places it in the correct sorted position automatically. (May cause fragmentation if not managed.)
